Get the data

Access the CDC page

Download the data from the CDC website.

Create a folder somewhere in your computer for your R project. Create a data folder inside the project folder, and place the data file inside the data folder.

Start new RStudio project

  1. Go to File > New Project
  2. Click on Existing Directory
  3. Browse... to where your project folder is
  4. Click Create Project to open your project session

Load library

We will be using tidyverse for this lesson. Remember to run install.packages("tidyverse") if you don’t have this package installed yet.

library(tidyverse)

We are now ready to read data in.

Read data in

Use read_csv() with the path to your data file to read the data in.

vaccine_hesitancy <- read_csv("data/Vaccine_Hesitancy_for_COVID-19__County_and_local_estimates.csv")

You can inspect your data using view(vaccine_hesitancy).

Data analysis

Percent of adults in Arizona that are fully vaccinated

What percentage of the adult population in Arizona are fully vaccinated against COVID-19? Which Arizona county has the highest percentage of adult population vaccinated? Which county has the lowest percentage?

Steps:

  1. start with the dataframe object vaccine_hesitancy and then (remember that and then is how we read the pipe, or %>%)
  2. filter to keep State equals (==) “ARIZONA” (state names are all capitalized) and then
  3. select the columns of interest to display to answer the questions above, which in this case are the columns County Name and Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19. Remember to use backtick (') around column names that contain space. And then …
  4. arrange by Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19 to get an orderd results tables from the lowest to the highest percentage
vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  filter(State == "ARIZONA") %>%
  select(`County Name`, `Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`) %>%
  arrange(`Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`)

ANSWER: Mohave County has the lowest percentage of their adult population fully vaccinated (25.5%), while Pima County has the highest percentage (69.8%).

We can get measures of centrality (e.g., mean) and variability (e.g., standard deviation) in the state of Arizona by using summarize() with functions like mean() and sd().

vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  filter(State == "ARIZONA") %>%
  summarize(mean_percent = mean(`Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`),
            sd_percent = sd(`Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   mean_percent sd_percent
##          <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1        0.448      0.117

Overall, on average, 44.8% of the adult population in Arizona across different counties are fully vaccinated (11 percent points for standard deviation).

Hesitancy in getting the COVID-19 vaccine in Arizona

To understand how hesitancy is defined, here are the descriptions for the three types found on the CDC website:

"We use three definitions to capture the strength of hesitancy to receive a vaccine.

  • Strongly hesitant: includes only survey responses indicating that they would definitely not receive a COVID-19 vaccine when available.
  • Hesitant: includes survey responses indicating that they would “probably not” or definitely not receive a COVID-19 vaccine when available.
  • Hesitant or unsure: includes survey responses indicating that they would probably not or unsure or definitely not receive a COVID-19 vaccine when available."

We will follow these steps:

  1. start with vaccine_hesitancy and then
  2. filter the data to keep State that is equal to “ARIZONA”
  3. select the columns County Name, Estimated hesitant, Estimated hesitant or unsure, and Estimated strongly hesitant
vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  filter(State == "ARIZONA") %>%
  select(`County Name`,
         `Estimated hesitant`,
         `Estimated hesitant or unsure`,
         `Estimated strongly hesitant`)

Relationship between level of concern and vaccination rates in adults

What is the relationship between level of concern and vaccination rates in adults across the United States?

Understand variables

To answer the question for this session, we will be using the CVAC Level Of Concern variable. Let’s first take a look at how many observations we have for each unique value in this categorical variable.

vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  count(`CVAC Level Of Concern`)
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   `CVAC Level Of Concern`     n
##   <chr>                   <int>
## 1 High Concern              628
## 2 Low Concern               628
## 3 Moderate Concern          628
## 4 Very High Concern         629
## 5 Very Low Concern          629

We can use group_by() with summarize() to get the mean estimated hisitancy per level of concern. We follow these steps:

  1. start with vaccine_hesitancy and then
  2. group by CVAC Level Of Concern and then
  3. summarize the mean of Estimated hesitant or unsure and then
  4. arrange by your newly created mean variable (created inside summarize in the previous step)
vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  group_by(`CVAC Level Of Concern`) %>%
  summarize(mean_hesitancy = mean(`Estimated hesitant or unsure`)) %>%
  arrange(mean_hesitancy)
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   `CVAC Level Of Concern` mean_hesitancy
##   <chr>                            <dbl>
## 1 Very Low Concern                 0.180
## 2 Low Concern                      0.187
## 3 Moderate Concern                 0.199
## 4 High Concern                     0.219
## 5 Very High Concern                0.228

It seems that Very Low Concern has the lowest hesitancy (or unsureness) percentace, while Very High Concern has the highest hesitancy (or unsureness) percentage.

Get summary table

Here’s a reminder of our data question:

What is the relationship between level of concern and vaccination rates in adults across the United States?

We can answer this question by creating a table very similar to the last table we created, by grouping by CVAC Level Of Concern and then calculating not only the mean of Estimated hesitant or unsure but also the mean of Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19.

Here are our steps:

  1. start with vaccine_hesitancy and then
  2. group by CVAC Level Of Concern and then
  3. summarize the mean of Estimated hesitant or unsure and the mean of Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19 (make sure you use ra.rm = TRUE inside mean() to ignore missing values) and then
  4. arrange by your newly created mean variable (created inside summarize in the previous step)
vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  group_by(`CVAC Level Of Concern`) %>%
  summarize(mean_hesitancy = mean(`Estimated hesitant or unsure`),
            mean_vacc_rate = mean(`Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(mean_hesitancy)
## # A tibble: 5 x 3
##   `CVAC Level Of Concern` mean_hesitancy mean_vacc_rate
##   <chr>                            <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Very Low Concern                 0.180          0.414
## 2 Low Concern                      0.187          0.367
## 3 Moderate Concern                 0.199          0.339
## 4 High Concern                     0.219          0.317
## 5 Very High Concern                0.228          0.270

Visualize raw data

Another way to get to the relationship between Estimated hesitant or unsure and Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19 is by plotting a scatterplot of these two numeric variables (map one variable to x and another to y). We can add a linear regression line with geom_smooth().

vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`,
             y = `Estimated hesitant or unsure`)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

How would you interpret the plot above? What is the relationship between Estimated hesitant or unsure and Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19?

Visualize summarized data

We can plot results of our group_by + summarize that we did before, adding State to our group_by to get a summarization of the mean of Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19 by different CVAC Level Of Concern and State.

Our steps here are:

  1. start with vaccine_hesitancy and then
  2. group by State and CVAC Level Of Concern and then
  3. summarize the mean of Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19 (ignoring missing data) and then
  4. use mutate to rearrange the levels in the categorical variable CVAC Level Of Concern so these display in the correct order and then
  5. start a plot by mapping CVAC Level Of Concern to y and the mean created in summarize() to x, add
  6. a column geometrics with geom_col, add
  7. a facet by State (optionally set number of facet columns to 3), and add
  8. a label to x that is easy to understand
vaccine_hesitancy %>%
  group_by(State, `CVAC Level Of Concern`) %>%
  summarize(mean_vacc_rate = mean(`Percent adults fully vaccinated against COVID-19`, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(`CVAC Level Of Concern` = factor(`CVAC Level Of Concern`,
                                          levels = c("Very Low Concern",
                                                     "Low Concern",
                                                     "Moderate Concern",
                                                     "High Concern",
                                                     "Very High Concern"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = `CVAC Level Of Concern`,
             x = mean_vacc_rate)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~State, ncol = 3) +
  labs(x = "mean adult vaccination rate (percentage of adult population)")

> REFLECTION: How does Arizona compare to other states in terms of the COVID-19 vaccine level of concern? How would you explain the missing data for some states?
